  Commit 2 — chore: bootstrap Next.js project
  
  This runs create-next-app with the project's chosen stack. What gets created:

  - package.json — lists dependencies: Next.js 16, React 19, TypeScript, Tailwind CSS v4, shadcn/ui, motion, @gsap/react, geist font package
  - tsconfig.json — TypeScript config with "strict": true, path aliases (@/* → ./), target: "ES2017", lib: ["dom", "ES2017"]. Strict mode means TypeScript will error on any, unannotated function returns, null access — intentional because
  bugs in production are harder than compiler errors
  - next.config.ts — Next.js config file. Important: in Next.js 16 this is .ts not .js
  - tailwind.config.js — should NOT exist per AGENTS.md (Tailwind v4 uses @theme in CSS instead). Gets removed/replaced in the next commit
  - app/layout.tsx — root layout. Loads Geist Sans and Geist Mono via next/font (zero layout shift, fonts bundled at build time, not fetched from Google at runtime)
  - app/globals.css — base CSS with @import "tailwindcss" (Tailwind v4 syntax) and @theme {} block for the design tokens

  Why Next.js 16? The project is an App Router SaaS. Next.js 16 adds async cookies(), renames middleware.ts to proxy.ts, and tightens Server Component boundaries. These are all used throughout the project.

