  Commit 3 — SALEB-23 - feat: add landing page, auth shell, and dashboard skeleton
  
  This builds the visible shell — the routes and pages exist even before any real data flows through them.

  Directory structure created
  
  app/
    (public)/          ← marketing pages, no auth needed
      page.tsx         ← landing page
    (auth)/
      sign-in/
        page.tsx       ← sign-in page (wraps the card component)
        _components/
          sign-in-card.tsx  ← the actual sign-in UI
        actions.ts     ← server function (stub at this point)
    (dashboard)/
      page.tsx         ← dashboard home
      layout.tsx       ← dashboard layout (sidebar, nav)
      _components/     ← dashboard-specific components

  Why route groups with parentheses?

  (public), (auth), (dashboard) are Next.js route groups. The parentheses mean the folder name is NOT part of the URL. So app/(dashboard)/page.tsx serves /dashboard, not /(dashboard). This lets you have different layouts for different
  sections without polluting the URL.

  Why _components/ inside route folders?

  Convention from AGENTS.md. A _components/ folder is co-located with the route it belongs to — only that route uses those components. Shared components go to components/shared/. This prevents accidental reuse of something that was never
  designed to be reused.

  app/globals.css — Tailwind v4 design tokens

  @theme {
    --primary: 258 90% 66%;         /* violet */
    --background: 240 10% 3.9%;     /* near-black */
    --card: 240 8% 6%;
    --muted: 240 5% 10%;
    --border: 240 5% 12%;
  }

  In Tailwind v4, there is no tailwind.config.js. You define your design tokens directly in CSS using the @theme {} block. Tailwind reads these at build time and generates utility classes (bg-background, text-primary, etc.). If you need to
  add a new color, you add it here — not in a config file.

  motion from "motion/react" (not framer-motion)

  Every animation uses import { motion } from "motion/react". This is the motion package (motion.dev), which is the successor to Framer Motion. The package name is motion, import path is "motion/react". Never use framer-motion — it's a
  different package.

