  Commit 4 — SALEB-34 - feat: add postgresql schema with drizzle orm and pgvector

  This defines the entire database. Understanding this commit is critical because every other feature reads/writes these tables.

  New files

  lib/db/index.ts — the Drizzle client singleton

  import { drizzle } from "drizzle-orm/postgres-js";
  import postgres from "postgres";

  const client = postgres(process.env.DATABASE_URL!);
  export const db = drizzle(client, { schema });

  Why a singleton? In a Node.js server (Next.js), the module is loaded once. If you created a new connection on every import, you'd exhaust the Postgres connection pool. process.env.DATABASE_URL! — the ! tells TypeScript "I know this is
  defined". If it isn't at runtime, Postgres will throw immediately on first query, which is the right behavior (fail loudly, not silently).

  lib/db/schema.ts — all table definitions. Key tables:

  - users — stores who signed in via Microsoft Entra. tenantId links to their Azure AD tenant. email, name, avatarUrl come from the OAuth profile.
  - websites — a user registers their website URL here. verifiedAt tracks if they've proved ownership.
  - scans — each time a website is crawled, a row is created here. status is an enum (pending → running → completed/failed). rawCrawl is JSONB — stores the raw Firecrawl output so we can re-process without re-crawling.
  - issues — SEO problems found during a scan. type is the problem category (missing-h1, duplicate-meta, etc.). fixType is either quick (one-click fix) or major (requires manual work). resolvedAt tracks when it was fixed.
  - cmsConnections — credentials/tokens for connecting to the user's CMS (WordPress, Webflow, etc.). credentialsRef stores a reference to Azure Key Vault, not the credentials themselves.
  - changeSnapshots — when an issue is auto-fixed via the CMS connection, a before/after snapshot is stored here. This is the audit trail.
  - aeoMentions — tracks brand mentions in AI answer engines (ChatGPT, Perplexity, Gemini, Claude). mentionEmbedding is a vector(1536) column — this requires pgvector. It stores the semantic embedding of the snippet so you can do similarity
  searches ("find mentions similar to this one").

  Why vector(1536)?

  1536 is the output dimension of OpenAI's text-embedding-ada-002 model and text-embedding-3-small. When we generate an embedding for a mention, we store those 1536 floats. Later we can use <=> (cosine distance operator from pgvector) to
  find semantically similar mentions.

  Why soft deletes (deletedAt)?

  Every table has deletedAt timestamp. Instead of DELETE FROM websites WHERE id = ?, we do UPDATE websites SET deleted_at = NOW() WHERE id = ?. This means:
  - Deleted data is recoverable
  - Foreign keys don't break (scan still references website even if website is "deleted")
  - Audit history is preserved

  When querying, you always add .where(isNull(schema.websites.deletedAt)) to exclude soft-deleted rows.

  drizzle.config.ts

  Drizzle Kit (the migration tool) reads this to know where your schema is and where to write migrations:

  export default {
    schema: "./lib/db/schema.ts",
    out: "./drizzle",
    dialect: "postgresql",
    dbCredentials: { url: process.env.DATABASE_URL! },
  };

  npm run db:migrate → runs drizzle-kit push → applies schema to the database.

