  Commit 5 — SALEB-38 - feat: add azure queue storage and functions async scan pipeline
  
  This is the async background processing architecture. Understanding this is key because all scan jobs flow through it.

  The problem it solves

  A website crawl takes 30–120 seconds. You cannot do that in a Next.js Route Handler (request timeout). The solution: when a user triggers a scan, you put a message on a queue (< 1ms), return HTTP 200 immediately, and an Azure Function
  processes the actual crawl in the background.

  lib/queue/types.ts

  export const ScanJobMessageSchema = z.object({
    scanId: z.string().uuid(),
    websiteId: z.string().uuid(),
    enqueuedAt: z.string().datetime(),
  });
  export const QUEUE_NAMES = {
    SCAN_JOBS: "scan-jobs",
    DEAD_LETTER: "scan-jobs-poison",
  };

  Why Zod here? The message goes through Azure Queue Storage as a JSON string. When the Function receives it, it parses back to JSON. ScanJobMessageSchema.parse(msg) validates that the parsed JSON has the exact shape we expect — if someone
  accidentally sends a malformed message, it fails loudly at the parse step, not silently later when scanId is undefined.

  lib/queue/client.ts

  import { QueueServiceClient } from "@azure/storage-queue";

  let _client: QueueServiceClient | null = null;

  export function getQueueClient(): QueueServiceClient {
    if (!_client) {
      _client = QueueServiceClient.fromConnectionString(
        process.env.AZURE_STORAGE_CONNECTION_STRING!
      );
    }
    return _client;
  }

  Singleton pattern again — one connection, reused across requests. fromConnectionString parses the Azure connection string (which contains the account name, key, and endpoint) and creates the client.

  lib/queue/enqueue-scan.ts

  export async function enqueueScan(websiteId: string, scanId: string) {
    const client = getQueueClient();
    const queue = client.getQueueClient(QUEUE_NAMES.SCAN_JOBS);
    await queue.createIfNotExists();
    const msg = JSON.stringify({ scanId, websiteId, enqueuedAt: new Date().toISOString() });
    await queue.sendMessage(Buffer.from(msg).toString("base64"));
  }

  Azure Queue Storage requires messages to be base64-encoded. If you send raw JSON, the Azure portal and Azure Functions runtime both complain. Buffer.from(msg).toString("base64") encodes the JSON string. The Function runtime automatically
  decodes it back when it receives the trigger.

  azure-functions/ — separate Node.js project

  This is a completely separate Node.js project from the Next.js app. It has its own package.json, tsconfig.json, node_modules/. Why? Azure Functions deploys independently from the web app — it runs on a separate Azure Functions App Service
  plan, not inside Next.js.

  azure-functions/host.json

  {
    "extensions": {
      "queues": { "maxDequeueCount": 5 }
    }
  }

  maxDequeueCount: 5 — if a message is dequeued (picked up by a Function) and not deleted within the lock timeout (by default 30s), Azure puts it back on the queue. If this happens 5 times, Azure moves the message to the poison queue
  (scan-jobs-poison). This prevents infinite retry loops from a broken message crashing the Function repeatedly. You then inspect the poison queue to find the bad message.

  azure-functions/src/functions/scan-worker.ts

  app.storageQueue("scanWorker", {
    queueName: "scan-jobs",
    connection: "AZURE_STORAGE_CONNECTION_STRING",
    handler: async (message, context) => {
      const { scanId, websiteId } = ScanJobMessageSchema.parse(message);
      await db.update(scans).set({ status: "running" }).where(eq(scans.id, scanId));
      // ... do the actual crawl work ...
      await db.update(scans).set({ status: "completed" }).where(eq(scans.id, scanId));
    }
  });

  This is the Azure Functions v4 model. You call app.storageQueue(...) to register a queue-triggered function. The handler receives the decoded message object. The function:
  1. Validates the message shape (Zod)
  2. Updates the scan status to running in the DB (so the UI can show a spinner)
  3. Does the actual work (Firecrawl crawl — added in later commits)
  4. Updates status to completed or failed 

  If step 3 throws an uncaught error, the function fails, the message is NOT deleted from the queue, Azure retries up to maxDequeueCount times.

  azure-functions/src/functions/rescan-timer.ts

  app.timer("rescanTimer", {
    schedule: "0 0 * * 0",  // every Sunday at midnight
    handler: async () => {
      const stale = await db.select()
        .from(websites)
        .where(/* no scan in last 7 days */);
      for (const site of stale) {
        const scan = await db.insert(scans).values({ websiteId: site.id, status: "pending" }).returning();
        await enqueueScan(site.id, scan[0].id);
      }
    }
  });

  The timer uses a cron expression: 0 0 * * 0 = minute 0, hour 0, any day-of-month, any month, day-of-week 0 (Sunday). Every Sunday at midnight UTC, this runs and re-queues any website that hasn't been scanned in 7 days.

  Cross-project TypeScript imports

  The Azure Functions code imports from the Next.js app's lib/ directory:

  import { db } from "../lib/db";              // azure-functions/src/lib/db.ts
  import { scans } from "../../../lib/db/schema"; // saleboom_seo/lib/db/schema.ts

  The tsconfig.json in azure-functions/ has "rootDir": ".." which sets the root to the parent saleboom_seo/ folder. This means TypeScript can see both azure-functions/src/ and saleboom_seo/lib/ in the same compilation. The ../../../ path
  from src/functions/ goes: up to src/, up to azure-functions/, up to saleboom_seo/, then into lib/.

