  Commit 8 — SALEB-41 - feat: add auth.js nextauth v5 microsoft entra id and proxy protection
  
  This is the authentication layer. Every protected page flows through this.

  lib/auth.ts — the core auth config

  import NextAuth from "next-auth";
  import MicrosoftEntraID from "next-auth/providers/microsoft-entra-id";

  export const { handlers, auth, signIn, signOut } = NextAuth({
    providers: [
      MicrosoftEntraID({
        clientId: process.env.AZURE_AD_CLIENT_ID!,
        clientSecret: process.env.AZURE_AD_CLIENT_SECRET!,
        issuer: `https://login.microsoftonline.com/${process.env.AZURE_AD_TENANT_ID}/v2.0`,
      }),
    ],
    session: { strategy: "jwt" },
    pages: { signIn: "/sign-in" },
    callbacks: { jwt(...), session(...) }
  });

  Why issuer with tenant ID? Without a tenant-specific issuer, the OAuth flow would accept logins from ANY Microsoft account (personal, any company). By specifying https://login.microsoftonline.com/{TENANT_ID}/v2.0, only accounts from your
  specific Azure AD tenant can log in. This is single-tenant auth.

  session: { strategy: "jwt" } — the session is stored in a signed JWT cookie, not in a database table. Pros: no session table needed, scales horizontally (any server can verify the cookie). Cons: you can't "invalidate" a session server-side
  until the JWT expires. Fine for this project since it's an internal tool.

  JWT callback — extracts id and tenantId from the token and puts them in the JWT:
  jwt({ token, user, profile }) {
    if (user?.id) token.id = user.id;
    if (profile && "tid" in profile) token.tenantId = profile.tid as string;
    return token;
  }
  profile.tid is the Azure AD tenant ID from the ID token claims. We store it so we can verify it later if needed.

  Session callback — copies those values from the JWT into the session object:
  session({ session, token }) {
    session.user.id = token.id as string;
    session.user.tenantId = token.tenantId as string;
    return session;
  }
  This is why session.user.id and session.user.tenantId are available in Server Components.

  Module augmentation:
  declare module "next-auth" {
    interface Session {
      user: { id: string; tenantId?: string } & DefaultSession["user"];
    } 
  }
  By default, session.user only has name, email, image. This tells TypeScript that our session also has id and tenantId. Without this, session.user.id would be a TypeScript error.

  app/api/auth/[...nextauth]/route.ts

  import { handlers } from "@/lib/auth";
  export const { GET, POST } = handlers;

  This is a catch-all route — the [...nextauth] segment matches any sub-path. Auth.js uses multiple paths: /api/auth/signin, /api/auth/callback/microsoft-entra-id, /api/auth/session, etc. The handlers object from Auth.js handles all of them.
  You just re-export GET and POST.

  proxy.ts — the route guard

  export const proxy = auth((request) => {
    const isProtected = request.nextUrl.pathname.startsWith("/dashboard");
    if (isProtected && !request.auth) {
      const signInUrl = new URL("/sign-in", request.url);
      signInUrl.searchParams.set("callbackUrl", pathname + search);
      return NextResponse.redirect(signInUrl);
    }
    return NextResponse.next();
  });

  This is Next.js 16's equivalent of middleware.ts (renamed to proxy.ts). It runs on every request before any page renders. auth(handler) is a wrapper from Auth.js — it verifies the JWT cookie and attaches the session to request.auth.

  If the path starts with /dashboard and request.auth is null (not logged in), it redirects to /sign-in and appends the attempted URL as callbackUrl so after login the user goes back to where they were trying to go.

  Critical comment in the file: proxy.ts is a FIRST-LINE redirect check only. It is NOT the sole auth check. Why? Because:
  - The proxy only runs on browser navigation, not on direct API calls
  - Server Functions (use server) must also call auth() independently
  - Route Handlers must also verify the session independently

  This is defence-in-depth. If someone finds a way to bypass the proxy, the Server Functions still protect the data.

  config.matcher — tells Next.js which paths this proxy runs on:
  "/((?!_next/static|_next/image|favicon.ico|sitemap.xml|robots.txt|.*\\.(?:svg|png|jpg|...)$).*)"
  Excludes static files, images, and the _next/ build output. If you didn't exclude these, every image request would go through the auth check, slowing down the page.

  lib/auth-utils.ts

  export async function getServerSession(): Promise<Session> {
    const session = await auth();
    if (!session) redirect("/sign-in");
    return session;
  }
  
  This is a convenience wrapper for Server Components. Instead of writing the null-check everywhere, you call getServerSession() at the top of any dashboard page. If not logged in, it redirects. If logged in, it returns the typed Session.

  app/(auth)/sign-in/actions.ts

  "use server";
  export async function signInWithMicrosoft() {
    await signIn("microsoft-entra-id", { redirectTo: "/dashboard" });
  }

  "use server" marks this as a Server Function. When called from a form action attribute, it runs on the server, not in the browser. signIn("microsoft-entra-id", ...) triggers the OAuth redirect to Microsoft's login page. After the user logs
  in on Microsoft's side, they're redirected back to /api/auth/callback/microsoft-entra-id, the JWT is set, and they land on /dashboard.

  sign-in-card.tsx — the sign-in UI

  <form action={signInWithMicrosoft}>
    <Button type="submit">Continue with Microsoft</Button>
  </form>

  The action prop on a <form> can be a Server Function in Next.js App Router. When the form is submitted, the browser POSTs to the server, which calls signInWithMicrosoft(). No JavaScript required for the initial redirect — works even with
  JS disabled.

  What to check if auth breaks:
  - AUTH_SECRET env var missing → JWT signing fails
  - AZURE_AD_CLIENT_ID / AZURE_AD_CLIENT_SECRET wrong → OAuth returns 400
  - Redirect URI in Azure AD app registration must match {your-domain}/api/auth/callback/microsoft-entra-id
  - AZURE_AD_TENANT_ID wrong → "unauthorized_client" error

