  Commit 9 — SALEB-44 - feat: add firecrawl sdk wrapper with typed scrape and crawl

  lib/crawl/types.ts — Zod schemas

  export const PageResultSchema = z.object({
    url: z.string(),
    markdown: z.string().optional(),
    html: z.string().optional(),
    links: z.array(z.string()).optional(),
    metadata: PageMetadataSchema.optional(),
  });

  export const CrawlResultSchema = z.object({
    jobId: z.string(),
    total: z.number(),
    pages: z.array(PageResultSchema),
  });

  Why define our own Zod types on top of the SDK's TypeScript types? Two reasons:
  1. Validation at the boundary — the SDK returns Document objects from Firecrawl. If the self-hosted Firecrawl returns an unexpected shape (version mismatch, config issue), PageResultSchema.parse(...) throws a clear Zod error with the exact
  field that failed, instead of a Cannot read property 'markdown' of undefined somewhere deep in your code.
  2. Serializable types — Zod schemas can be exported and reused in Server Functions, queue messages, and DB writes. TypeScript interfaces cannot enforce runtime validation.

  PageMetadataSchema captures the SEO-relevant metadata fields: title, description, language, URL, Open Graph tags (ogTitle, ogDescription, ogImage), and statusCode (HTTP status — crucial for detecting 404s and redirects during a crawl).

  lib/crawl/firecrawl-client.ts — the wrapper

  const client = createClient();

  function createClient(): Firecrawl {
    return new Firecrawl({
      apiKey: process.env.FIRECRAWL_API_KEY,
      apiUrl: process.env.FIRECRAWL_API_URL ?? "http://localhost:3002",
      timeoutMs: process.env.FIRECRAWL_TIMEOUT_MS ? Number(process.env.FIRECRAWL_TIMEOUT_MS) : 30_000,
      maxRetries: 3,
      backoffFactor: 2,
    });
  }

  apiUrl defaults to http://localhost:3002 — this is for local development with self-hosted Firecrawl. In production, you set FIRECRAWL_API_URL to your deployed Firecrawl instance URL.

  maxRetries: 3, backoffFactor: 2 — the SDK handles retries internally. With backoffFactor 2: retry 1 after ~1s, retry 2 after ~2s, retry 3 after ~4s. This handles transient network errors and momentary Firecrawl overload without hammering
  the service.

  export { SdkError as FirecrawlError, JobTimeoutError as FirecrawlTimeoutError } — re-exported under friendlier names. In your scan worker, you can write:
  import { scrapeUrl, FirecrawlError, FirecrawlTimeoutError } from "@/lib/crawl/firecrawl-client";
  try {
    const result = await scrapeUrl(url);
  } catch (e) {
    if (e instanceof FirecrawlTimeoutError) {
      // timeout — retry later
    } else if (e instanceof FirecrawlError) {
      // API error — log and mark scan failed
    }
  }

  scrapeUrl — scrapes a single URL, parses the result through PageResultSchema. onlyMainContent: true strips navigation, footers, ads — you get just the article/page body in markdown, which is what you want for SEO analysis.

  crawlSite — the client.crawl() method is a convenience waiter — it starts the crawl job, polls until completion, and returns the full CrawlJob with all pages in job.data. limit: 100 caps the crawl at 100 pages — prevents runaway costs on
  large sites.

  What to check if Firecrawl fails:
  - Is Docker running? docker ps | grep firecrawl
  - Is the port right? curl http://localhost:3002/health
  - FIRECRAWL_API_KEY must match what Firecrawl expects (any string for self-hosted)
  - Timeout errors → increase FIRECRAWL_TIMEOUT_MS

