  Commit 10 — SALEB-46 - feat: add azure openai client via vercel ai sdk with structured generation

  lib/ai/client.ts — Azure OpenAI singleton

  const azure = createAzure({
    baseURL: process.env.AZURE_OPENAI_ENDPOINT,
    apiKey: process.env.AZURE_OPENAI_API_KEY,
    apiVersion: process.env.AZURE_OPENAI_API_VERSION,
  });

  export function getModel(deploymentId?: string): LanguageModelV4 {
    const id = deploymentId ?? process.env.AZURE_OPENAI_DEPLOYMENT;
    if (!id) throw new Error("AZURE_OPENAI_DEPLOYMENT is not set");
    return azure.chat(id);
  }

  Why baseURL not resourceName? The env var is AZURE_OPENAI_ENDPOINT which is a full URL (e.g. https://my-resource.openai.azure.com). The SDK supports either resourceName (it constructs the URL) or baseURL (you give the full URL). Using
  baseURL is more explicit and supports non-standard deployments.

  azure.chat(deploymentId) — creates a model object bound to that specific Azure OpenAI deployment. The deployment name (e.g. gpt-4o) must match what you created in Azure AI Studio. If it doesn't match, you get a 404 from the Azure API.

  getModel() throws if no deployment set — better than silently using undefined as the model ID, which would give a confusing API error.

  lib/ai/generate.ts — generateStructured<T>()

  export async function generateStructured<T>(
    schema: z.ZodSchema<T>,
    prompt: string,
    opts?: { system?: string; deploymentId?: string }
  ): Promise<T> {
    const model = getModel(opts?.deploymentId);
    const result = await generateText({
      model,
      output: Output.object({ schema }),
      system: opts?.system,
      prompt,
    });
    return result.output as T;
  }

  Why generateText with Output.object() instead of generateObject()?
  generateObject is marked @deprecated in the installed version (AI SDK v7). The new API separates the model call (generateText) from the output format (Output.object({ schema })). The output option tells the SDK to use structured output
  mode — the model is instructed to return JSON matching the schema, and the SDK validates and parses it.

  result.output as T — result.output is typed as InferCompleteOutput<typeof output> which the TypeScript compiler can't simplify to T in a generic context. The as T cast is safe because the schema IS ZodSchema<T> — if the Zod validation
  passes, the value is T.

  opts?.system — the system prompt. For SEO suggestions this would be something like "You are an SEO expert. Analyse the provided page content and return optimised metadata." For AEO mention extraction: "You are extracting brand mentions
  from AI answer engine outputs."

  Schemas

  seo-suggestions.ts:
  z.object({
    metaTitle: z.string().describe("Optimised page title (50-60 chars)"),
    metaDescription: z.string().describe("Optimised meta description (150-160 chars)"),
    h1: z.string().describe("Primary heading for the page"),
  })
  The .describe() calls are important — they're included in the JSON schema sent to the model, helping it understand what each field should contain.

  aeo-mentions.ts:
  z.enum(["chatgpt", "perplexity", "gemini", "claude", "other"])
  z.enum(["positive", "neutral", "negative"])
  These enum values match exactly the Postgres enum values in lib/db/schema.ts (aeoPlatformEnum, aeoSentimentEnum). This is intentional — when you insert an extracted mention into the DB, you don't need to transform it. The AI output goes
  straight into the DB.

  What to check if AI calls fail:
  - AZURE_OPENAI_ENDPOINT must end with the right path (no trailing / issues)
  - AZURE_OPENAI_API_VERSION must match the version your deployment supports (e.g. 2024-02-01)
  - AZURE_OPENAI_DEPLOYMENT must exactly match the deployment name in Azure AI Studio (case-sensitive)
  - If you get NoObjectGeneratedError — the model returned content that didn't match the schema; check your system prompt

